    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nwhen completing for a long pattern in cmdline, the matches showed in the pum can be very verbose, which is diffcult to spot the difference at first glance.\n\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/6e40d55e-973f-43c9-9ac8-870a7b5472ad)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nmaybe we can add an `offset` value to the return value of `:command-completion-custom` function to make the returned matches shorter: \n```\napi.nvim_create_user_command(,,{complete = function(...)\n  return {offset: integer, matches: string[]}\nend})\n```\n\nas a reference, vifm has `offset`` which make me believe that's possible for nvim too:\n\n> - \"offset\" (integer) (default: 0)\n   Offset from beginning of the argument.  This is useful to avoid prepending\n   prefix that's common to all matches, thus completing only essential part.\n   For example, in case of \"var=val\" use offset=4 to complete part after \"=\".\n - \"matches\" (array of strings or tables)\n\n(https://github.com/vifm/vifm/blob/v0.14.3/data/vim/doc/app/vifm-lua.txt#L863)",
    "closed_at": "2026-05-12T16:01:43Z",
